@Jay 

I lived in Tucson years ago. The soil in the desert there is mostly sand, and the rains during the summer monsoons are torrential (really...you have to see it to believe it). 

So you can have water invisibly wash away the underlying soil of a road in a spot, sometimes leaving a pretty large cavity, and be driving down said road that appears to be in great condition, and suddenly one wheel just disappears into an abyss that wasn't there a second ago, along with the piece of unsupported asphalt you just drove across. It's dramatic and dangerous and sudden and noisy, and usually expensive.

