I missed out on getting to know the Beatles through my parents, but my mother had done a postdoc in Europe and evidently returned with a secret fascination with ABBA. I say secret because the official PR version holds that she‚Äôs only ever listened to opera. But I found the ABBA tapes ca. the same time I rooted through her makeup bag for the first time. (I got caught with the makeup but not with the ABBA albums). To this day I can belt out By the Rivers of Babylon to the great consternation of our neighbors.

@Jane Wheelaghan 

Spinach, minced into a bland, glutinous, disgusting pulp, was often served at my kindergarten in the 80s - because it was healthy, supposedly. I hated it with a passion and could not force myself to swallow any of it. It took me some 20 years to recover from the trauma - I was served garlicky, well seasoned spinach in France (or was it Italy?) and instantly loved it. These days I use spinach in my own cooking, and enjoy palak sauces at Indian restaurants.

The spinach Popeye downs so gladly looks like the horror from my childhood though, which is why I never liked that cartoon.

@Jane Wheelaghan 

