Average time for me. Would have been several minutes faster if I hadn't gotten stuck with "WEEMOVE" and unable to figure out Bee-dazzler from that. Those crosses alone took me almost 10 minutes to fix.

@Mean Old Lady 

Canned asparagus! And frozen spinach -- watery and flavorless. Pretty much every vegetable was in frozen form in my childhood home:  square boxes, not those relatively decent bags you find in the freezer section these days... Squash, especially, tasted of the cardboard it came in. 

(Raises hand for discovering asparagus and spinach in fresh form as an adult.)

@G 

When I was young (4ish?), my dad was stationed in the Philippines. The only cartoon we got was Popeye. (I also remember Captain Kangaroo‚Äîmaybe part of the same broadcast?) My mom would buy canned spinach and, to get me to eat some kind of vegetable, she would wash out the can and put a bunch back in it and serve it to me ala‚Äô Popeye. I would hold my nose and gobble it down to get Popeye power. 

Worked in the short run, but took until well into my adulthood to start eating non-salad veggies; after learning that you could actually make them taste good, especially if you used fresh ones.

@Warren 

Speaking of salad veggies: Don't get me started on what passed for those in my youth! My mother still enjoys iceberg lettuce and I find it regularly in her refrigerator. The crunch is nice, I'll give her that... But otherwise it just gives me bad flashbacks! 

Even worse, "tomatoes" were pale, salmon-colored orbs that came in those single-row plastic grids wrapped in cellophane. Mealy, tasteless... Yuck!! Up until recently, I would only eat tomatoes in season. (Still far and away the best, but "capari" ones are a serviceable alternative at this time of year.) Yes, I'm a tomato snob!! Maybe Andrzej is a little like that with the white asparagus.  :)

